{{nihongo|'''Kaori Moriyama'''|<U+68EE><U+5C71> <U+304B><U+304A><U+308A>|Moriyama Kaori|extra=n<U+00E9>e '''Hachinohe''' {{nihongo||<U+516B><U+6238>|Hachinohe|}}; born 4 January 1964}} is a retired [[Japan]]ese [[judo|judoka]].

Moriyama is from [[Hakodate, Hokkaid<U+014D>]] and began judo at the age of a junior high school second grader <ref name="<U+8FD1><U+4EE3><U+67D4><U+9053>">{{cite news|publisher=Baseball Magazine Sha Co., Ltd|title=<U+8FD1><U+4EE3><U+67D4><U+9053>
2010<U+5E74>2<U+6708><U+53F7> <U+5165><U+9580><U+FF01><U+4E00><U+6D41><U+306E><U+6280><U+8853> -<U+7B2C>67<U+56DE> <U+68EE><U+5C71><U+304B><U+304A><U+308A>5<U+6BB5><U+306E><U+300C><U+5927><U+5916><U+5208><U+308A><U+300D>-|date=2010-02-20}}</ref>.

When she was a student of [[Tokai University]], she studied under former world champion, [[Nobuyuki Sato (judoka)|Nobuyuki Sato]]<ref name="<U+8FD1><U+4EE3><U+67D4><U+9053>"/> and got bronze medal of [[World Judo Championships|World Championships]] in 1984. In the next year, she won the gold medal at [[Asian Judo Championships|Asian Championships]], All-Japan Selected Championships, [[Kodokan Cup]] and All-Japan University Championships with her proud skill, [[Osotogari]] and [[Newaza]]<ref name="<U+8FD1><U+4EE3><U+67D4><U+9053>"/>

She retired and became a teacher of the senior high school in [[Hokkaid<U+014D>]] after graduation at a university in 1986. As of 2010, Moriyama coaches judo at high school in [[Kanagawa Prefecture]]. 

==Achievements==
*1979 - All-Japan Selected Championships (-65&nbsp;kg) ''2nd''
*1980 - All-Japan Selected Championships (-61&nbsp;kg) ''2nd''
*1981 - All-Japan Selected Championships (-61&nbsp;kg) ''2nd''
*1982 - All-Japan Selected Championships (-61&nbsp;kg) ''1st''
*1983 - All-Japan Selected Championships (-61&nbsp;kg) ''1st''
*1984 - [[World Judo Championships|World Championships]] (-61&nbsp;kg) ''3rd''
:: - All-Japan Selected Championships (-61&nbsp;kg) ''1st''
*1985 - [[Asian Judo Championships|Asian Championships]] (-61&nbsp;kg) ''1st''
:: - All-Japan Selected Championships (-61&nbsp;kg) ''1st''
:: - All-Japan University Championships (Openweight only) ''1st''
*1986 - [[All-Japan Judo Championships|All-Japan Championships]] (Openweight only) ''1st'' 

